===Historical note===
The patron saint of England is St George, while that of Scotland is St Andrew. (This heritage is reflected in the [[w:Union Flag|Union Flag]], on which the crosses of Sts George and Andrew are superimposed). The two neighbors have had a complicated relationship over the centuries, from friendly rivalry to bloody warfare. The name ''Geordie'' is a Scots diminutive form of ''George'', and naturally has been used by Scottish people as both a friendly nickname and a sarcastic pejorative for their southern neighbors. The coin called ''Geordie'' originally had an image of St George on it.

